      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        What Is a Form 6 Authority in Queensland Real Estate and What Sellers Should Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The Form 6 is the legal document that appoints your agent and sets the terms of their authority. Most sellers sign it without reading it. That is a mistake.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When you appoint a real estate agent to sell your property in Queensland, the document that formalises that appointment is called a Form 6. It is a statutory form prescribed under the Property Occupations Act 2014, and it is the legal instrument that authorises your agent to act on your behalf. Without a signed Form 6, an agent cannot legally market or sell your property in this state.</p>

      <p>Most vendors sign the Form 6 at the same meeting where they choose their agent, which is understandable, but it means the document rarely receives the scrutiny it warrants. The terms inside it govern your relationship with your agent for the length of the campaign, including what happens if things go well, what happens if they do not, and what you owe if you change your mind or change agents during the process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the Form 6 authorises your agent to do</h2>
      <p>The Form 6 sets out the scope of the agent's authority. In a standard sales appointment, this includes: marketing the property to prospective buyers, conducting open homes and private inspections, receiving and presenting offers to you, negotiating on price and terms on your behalf if you authorise this, and facilitating the execution of a contract of sale once you accept an offer.</p>

      <p>The Form 6 does not give the agent authority to accept an offer or commit you to a sale without your explicit consent. The agent presents offers; you accept or reject them. An agent who tells you they have accepted an offer on your behalf without your instruction has acted outside their authority under the Form 6. If this happens, seek legal advice immediately.</p>

      <p>The form also records whether the appointment is exclusive or open. An exclusive appointment means only the appointed agent may sell the property during the exclusive period, and commission is owed to them even if the sale is ultimately negotiated by another party or a buyer's agent. An open listing appointment allows multiple agents to be appointed simultaneously, with commission owed only to whichever agent introduces the ultimate buyer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The key terms to review before you sign</h2>
      <p>The exclusive period is the most important term for most vendors. This is the period during which only the appointed agent can sell the property. It must be specified as a defined number of days or a calendar period, it cannot be indefinite. Most agents propose 60 to 90 days. That is negotiable. If you are uncertain about the agent or want flexibility, you can propose a shorter exclusive period, though agents who invest significantly in marketing upfront reasonably expect a period long enough to run a proper campaign and attract serious buyers.</p>

      <p>Commission is typically expressed as a percentage of the sale price, plus GST. In Queensland, commission rates are not regulated and are negotiated between the vendor and the agent. The rate, and any minimum commission applicable, must be stated clearly in the Form 6. Read the commission clause carefully and confirm how it applies to different scenarios: a sale during the exclusive period, a sale outside the exclusive period but to a buyer introduced by the agent, and a sale after the appointment ends.</p>

      <p>Marketing expenses are listed separately and must be itemised in the Form 6. These typically include photography, copywriting, online listings, signage, and any print or social media advertising. These costs are usually payable whether or not the property sells, they are expenses for marketing services rendered, not a success fee. Confirm the total estimated marketing cost before signing and understand which items are fixed versus variable based on your campaign choices.</p>

      <p>Conjunctional arrangements refer to the agent's ability to work with other agencies or buyers' agents to facilitate a sale. The Form 6 should specify whether and how commission is shared in a conjunctional sale. Some agents restrict conjunctional access unless you explicitly authorise it. If you want maximum buyer exposure, make sure the Form 6 does not create a barrier to buyers' agents introducing qualified purchasers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens at the end of the exclusive period</h2>
      <p>When the exclusive period expires, the appointment typically converts to an open or general agency, meaning the agent continues to be authorised to sell but no longer has exclusivity. At this point you could also appoint additional agents without breaching the Form 6 terms. However, commission obligations may continue for buyers introduced during the exclusive period even after it has ended, this is the "tail" or "continuing obligation" period, and it is important to understand how it operates in your specific Form 6.</p>

      <p>The tail period means that if a buyer was introduced to your property during the exclusive period and later purchases, even weeks or months after the exclusive period ends and even if the transaction is facilitated by a different agent, commission may still be owed to the original agent. Tail periods and their terms vary. Read the relevant clause and, if the language is unclear, ask the agent to explain it in plain terms before you sign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Whether the Form 6 auto-renews and how to terminate it</h2>
      <p>A Form 6 appointment cannot automatically renew for a further exclusive period without a new signed authority. If your property has not sold by the end of the exclusive period, the appointment continues as a general authority unless you actively terminate it. An agent may ask you to sign a renewal or extension of the exclusive period at that point, that is a new Form 6 or an amendment to the existing one, and you are entitled to renegotiate the terms including the commission rate.</p>

      <p>To terminate a Form 6, you generally give written notice to the agent. The form itself will specify any notice requirements or fees applicable to early termination. There is no statutory cooling-off period for Form 6 appointments in Queensland, so you cannot simply change your mind within 48 hours without potential cost consequences, though agents often exercise discretion early in a campaign. If you want to change agents mid-campaign, get legal advice before acting to understand your commission exposure and ensure you comply with the termination provisions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Exclusive versus open listings in the Form 6</h2>
      <p>Exclusive listings give your agent a genuine incentive to invest in your campaign, they know they will be paid if the property sells during the period, regardless of which buyer source completes the transaction. That certainty supports a stronger marketing commitment. In Brisbane's inner east, exclusive campaigns consistently outperform open listings on days-on-market and price outcomes because the agent is more willing to spend and coordinate effectively when exclusivity is in place.</p>

      <p>Open listings are sometimes proposed for properties that have already failed to sell under an exclusive appointment with one agent, or where the vendor wants multiple agencies working simultaneously. The practical problem with open listings is that no single agent has an incentive to invest heavily, since another agency could introduce the buyer and claim the commission. The result is often passive marketing from multiple agents, with each waiting for the other to do the work. For most inner-east Brisbane properties, an exclusive appointment with the right agent produces better outcomes than an open listing with several mediocre ones.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common mistakes sellers make when signing</h2>
      <p>The most common mistake is signing at speed because the agent has asked you to confirm the appointment at the same meeting where you have just decided to list. Take the Form 6 away and read it before signing. If anything is unclear, ask for an explanation. An agent who pressures you to sign immediately without allowing time to read is giving you useful information about how they will operate throughout the campaign.</p>

      <p>A second mistake is not confirming the marketing cost itemisation. Some Form 6 agreements include a total marketing budget without detailing the line items, which gives the agent flexibility to allocate spend as they see fit. Ask for the breakdown and confirm which items you are committed to regardless of outcome.</p>

      <p>Third, many vendors sign an overly long exclusive period without considering whether it is appropriate for their property type and current market conditions. If the average days-on-market for comparable properties in your suburb is 21 days, a 90-day exclusive period is significantly longer than needed. Negotiate a period that reflects realistic campaign timing.</p>

      <p>Finally, verify that the agent signing the Form 6 holds a current Queensland real estate licence. Your Form 6 is only valid if signed by or on behalf of a licensed agent. You can check licence status through the Queensland Office of Fair Trading's public register.</p>

